<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,357,644]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,431,457]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
In contrast to the diagnosis given by Jacobs (
<number box="[901,964,432,458]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" value="1978.0">1978</number>
), in some species (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Stebbing, 1911" authorityName="Stebbing" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Sphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annandalei">
<emphasis box="[1269,1436,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">S. annandalei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stebbing" box="[151,343,469,495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Stebbing, T. R. R. (1911) Indian Isopods. Records of the Indian Museum, 6 (4), 179 - 191." type="journal article" year="1911">
Stebbing, 
<number box="[279,343,469,495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" value="1911.0">1911</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[358,459,469,494]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Sphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[358,459,469,494]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">S. silvai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[469,571,469,495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[469,571,469,495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
) inferior margins of maxilliped palp articles 
<number box="[1148,1195,469,495]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
have simple setae. Moreover, the semicircular distal margin of the maxilliped endite has in some species some plumose setae among the simple setae (e.g. 
<taxonomicName box="[495,656,544,569]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Sphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annandalei">
<emphasis box="[495,656,544,569]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">S. annandalei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stebbing, 1905" authorityName="Stebbing" authorityYear="1905" box="[672,977,544,570]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Sphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="walkeri">
<emphasis box="[672,790,544,569]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">S. walkeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Stebbing" box="[798,977,544,570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="44" refString="Stebbing, T. R. R. (1905) Report to the Government of Ceylon on the pearl oyster fisheries of the Gulf of Manaar. Report on the Isopoda collected by Professor Herdman, at Ceylon, in 1902. Ceylon Pearl Oyster Fisheries, 1905, supplementary reports 23, 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="1905">
Stebbing, 
<number box="[916,977,544,570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" value="1905.0">1905</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1041,1134,544,569]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sphaeromatidae" genus="Sphaeroma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1041,1134,544,569]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">S. silvai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1142,1237,543,569]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1142,1237,543,569]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
). Pereopods 
<number box="[1392,1436,544,570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5</number>
are shorter than the other pereopods with the basis bearing inferiorly extended lobes; merus, carpus and propodus are short.
</paragraph>
